[Event "Paris — a night at the opera"]
[Site "Paris"]
[Date "1858.??.??"]
[White "Paul Morphy"]
[Black "Duke of Brunswick & Count Isouard"]
[Result "1-0"]
[Blurb "The most famous teaching game ever played. Morphy, the best player of his day, dispatched two amateurs consulting together — in a private box, mid-opera. A clinic in fast development and the attack it buys."]

1. e4 {Morphy plays the two amateurs while the opera carries on around them.} e5
2. Nf3 d6 {The Philidor Defence — safe, but it hems in Black's own bishop.}
3. d4 Bg4 {Pinning the knight. This bishop will end up costing Black dearly.}
4. dxe5 Bxf3 {Forced: on 4...dxe5 5. Qxd8+ Kxd8 Black loses the right to castle.}
5. Qxf3 dxe5
6. Bc4 {The bishop aims straight at f7 — the softest square in Black's camp.} Nf6
7. Qb3 {A double attack: the queen hits b7 and, with the bishop, f7.} Qe7
8. Nc3 {Pure Morphy. He passes up the free b7-pawn to keep every piece developing with threats.} c6
9. Bg5 b5
10. Nxb5 {The first sacrifice — lines and time are worth more than a knight.} cxb5
11. Bxb5+ Nbd7 {Now every white piece bears down on the pinned knight.}
12. O-O-O {He castles with tempo: the rook lands on the d-file, adding to the pin.} Rd8
13. Rxd7 {Tearing away the last defender.} Rxd7
14. Rd1 {The second rook joins. Black is completely tied up and can barely move.} Qe6
15. Bxd7+ Nxd7
16. Qb8+ {The finishing combination begins — a queen sacrifice to deflect the knight.} Nxb8
17. Rd8# {Checkmate. Down a queen and more, Morphy mates because every piece was working. The whole game is one long argument for rapid development.}
